 on a lively tour through this dazzling collection in which each piece tells a new story about food and the past. Packed with fascinating history, the volume is the first serious attempt to organize culinary ephemera into categories, making it useful for food lovers, collectors, designers, and curators alike. Much more than a catalog, Culinary Ephemera follows this paper trail to broader themes in American social history such as diet and health, alcoholic beverages, and Americans abroad. It is a collection that, as Weaver notes, will "transport us into the vicarious worlds of dinners past, brushing elbows with the reality of another time, another place, another human condition."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  a19th century.  a20th century.  aadvertisements.  aamerica.  abeauty.  abrochures.  acollection.  acollectors.  acuisine.  aculinary.  acurators.  adecorators.  adesigners.  adesigns.  adiet and health.  afood collectibles.  afood historians.  afood history.  afood labels.  afood lovers.  afood packaging.  afood stories.  afood.  ahistory.  ahuman condition.  aillustrated.  aimages.  akitchen setting.  alively.  amatch covers.  amenus.  amotifs.  apaper collectibles.  apast foods.  apostcards.  aposters.  asocial history.  avalentines.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025977540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094706140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947061/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000